00:00:06.239 --> 00:00:09.190
briefly talk about the history of HTML.

3
00:00:09.190 --> 00:00:11.850
Its usually the case that
the history of any technology

4
00:00:11.850 --> 00:00:14.410
is not particularly interesting or
exciting and

5
00:00:14.410 --> 00:00:18.030
I can't claim that the history of
HTML is that interesting either.

6
00:00:18.030 --> 00:00:21.360
But there are certain parts of this
history that not only give you

7
00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:24.860
an understanding of how this
technology was developed, but

8
00:00:24.860 --> 00:00:28.780
also gives you an appreciation
of certain aspects of HTML

9
00:00:28.780 --> 00:00:31.260
that are still relevant and
applicable today.

10
00:00:32.410 --> 00:00:35.880
So before 1997,
there were no community standards, so

11
00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:37.860
browsers basically did
whatever they wanted.

12
00:00:37.860 --> 00:00:40.250
They invented new tags.

13
00:00:40.250 --> 00:00:42.620
They implemented the same
tags differently.

14
00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:44.800
I was kind of the wild west of the web.

15
00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:48.330
And you could go to a website and

16
00:00:48.330 --> 00:00:52.860
end up being told that your browser is not
compatible with this website so you have

17
00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:57.510
to go get a different browser in order
to even view the website to begin with.

18
00:00:57.510 --> 00:01:03.260
Now around 1997 the World Wide
Web Consortium, the W3C, came up

19
00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:08.690
with the first standard browsers actually
started to pay somewhat attention to,

20
00:01:08.690 --> 00:01:13.960
which is HTML4 and
they very quickly updated it to HTML4.01.

21
00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:18.060
That standard was, pretty loose,
and, the browser's had, still had,

22
00:01:18.060 --> 00:01:22.480
way too much leeway inside that standard,

23
00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:27.530
as to how they implemented it, and
how pages we're being rendered.

24
00:01:27.530 --> 00:01:32.990
So, around 2000, the W3C came up
with another specification called

25
00:01:32.990 --> 00:01:38.040
XHTML 1.0 and
that specification was based on XML.

26
00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:43.190
And XML is a very rigid but
very clear markup language.

27
00:01:43.190 --> 00:01:48.240
In W3C wanted to kind of pick that up and
keep going, with it and produce XHTML 2.0.

28
00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:52.850
The problem is that the browser vendors
which at this point already had

29
00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:58.020
a history of not really listening a 100%
to any standard, they decided that

30
00:01:58.020 --> 00:02:02.630
this whole W3C thing is moving way
too slowly, and on top of that,

31
00:02:02.630 --> 00:02:07.330
they felt that the specifications
are really moving in the wrong direction.

32
00:02:07.330 --> 00:02:10.560
So the browsers banded together, the
browser vendors banded together and they

33
00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:16.780
created yet another group that produced
specifications that was called WHATWG.

34
00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:18.510
And WHATWG, that's yet

35
00:02:18.510 --> 00:02:21.150
another abbreviation because
we don't have enough of them.

36
00:02:21.150 --> 00:02:23.720
So that group is called WHATWG and

37
00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:28.350
it stands for Web Hypertext
Application Technology Group.

38
00:02:28.350 --> 00:02:31.140
So it's a bunch of browser
vendors that got together.

39
00:02:31.140 --> 00:02:34.250
And this group is much less
democratic than the W3C.

40
00:02:34.250 --> 00:02:40.450
In other words they have one central, one
editor that makes the final decisions so

41
00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:43.300
all the browser vendor representatives
can argue all they want but

42
00:02:43.300 --> 00:02:47.630
at the end the appointed one editor
that kind of makes the final decisions.

43
00:02:47.630 --> 00:02:51.000
And they're the ones that
are driving the entire HTML5,

44
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.420
what we have now,
they're the drivers behind it.

45
00:02:55.420 --> 00:03:00.330
So for a long time the two organizations
didn't really see eye to eye much at all

46
00:03:00.330 --> 00:03:01.440
and they didn't work together, so

47
00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:03.660
they were really going to
two different directions.

48
00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:07.690
But I think W3C eventually realized
that hey, you know, that organization is

49
00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:13.090
actually being driven by the people and
by the companies that actually matter.

50
00:03:13.090 --> 00:03:17.180
Because they are the guys who
are developing the browsers themselves,

51
00:03:17.180 --> 00:03:20.950
so maybe it's a good idea
to kind of make peace and

52
00:03:20.950 --> 00:03:23.100
try to see if we can
work together somehow.

53
00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:26.380
And this is what happened around 2007,
2009 time frame.

54
00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:30.490
So WHATWG and W3C started sort
of kind of working together.

55
00:03:30.490 --> 00:03:33.750
And what they produced in the end
is what we have now, HTML5.

56
00:03:33.750 --> 00:03:37.360
So what does any of that matter to you?

57
00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:41.860
Well what matters now is that there are
two organizations out there, one is called

58
00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:47.750
W3C and the other one is WHATWG and
they're both in charge of HTML somewhat.

59
00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:50.780
So it could be that you
could get into a situation,

60
00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:56.380
it's certainly possible that a browser
potentially can be compliant

61
00:03:56.380 --> 00:04:01.550
with a specification which isn't yet
even formalized by the official W3C.

62
00:04:01.550 --> 00:04:03.690
So, it makes your head spin a little bit,
doesn't it?

63
00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:09.350
So the way they divided it up is
that W3C is going to be in charge of

64
00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:12.960
the standards since this is what their
bread and butter is, its standards.

65
00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:16.470
And they are going to be in
charge of the HTML5 standard.

66
00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:20.450
And WHATWG is not even going to give
a version to their HTML standard,

67
00:04:20.450 --> 00:04:23.270
they're just going to say it's HTML and
it's constantly evolving.

68
00:04:23.270 --> 00:04:24.220
There is no version.

69
00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:25.270
We never stop.

70
00:04:25.270 --> 00:04:26.150
We keep evolving it.

71
00:04:26.150 --> 00:04:32.100
And that WHATWG, they're the ones
that really implement the browsers.

72
00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:37.050
So what W3C does is it kind of cherry
picks some of the more successful

73
00:04:37.050 --> 00:04:41.320
things that are actually kind of start
to be implemented by the browsers and

74
00:04:41.320 --> 00:04:45.490
they slowly bring it into
the official standard.

75
00:04:45.490 --> 00:04:47.990
So the point of this history,
this quick history lesson,

76
00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:51.020
is that this whole thing
is a bit of a muddy waters.

77
00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:53.670
And it's kind of hard
to keep track of well,

78
00:04:53.670 --> 00:04:57.300
what is the browser supposed
to be compliant with?

79
00:04:57.300 --> 00:05:00.650
But unfortunately it is our job as
developers to keep track of these

80
00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:02.040
capabilities.

81
00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:07.300
And it's particularly important
nowadays because all the major modern

